<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="scene">
<PB REF="3" MS="y">
<HEAD>THE Contrivances, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE the Street.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Robin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>_WELL! tho' Pimping is the mo&s;t honourable and profitable of all Profe&s;|&s;ions, it is certainly the mo&s;t dangerous and fa|tiguing; but of all Fa|tigues, there's none like following a vir|tuous Mi&s;tre&s;s&mdash;There's not one Letter I carry, but I run the Ri&s;que of kick|ing, caning, or pumping, nay often hang|ing&mdash;Let me &s;ee, I have committed three Burglaries already to get one Letter to her&mdash;Now if my Ma&s;ter &s;hou'd not get the Gyp|&s;y
<PB N="4" REF="4">
at la&s;t, I have ventur'd my &s;weet Per&s;on to a fair Purpo&s;e: He has nothing left but the Name of Captain and his Half Pay; which is as much as to &s;ay, that I his faith|ful Servant, and &s;o forth, mu&s;t come off with no Pay, or tru&s;t 'till Dooms-day&mdash;My Pockets are &s;o empty, that old Nick may &s;ecurely dance there, for there's not one Cro&s;s left to frighten him away&mdash;Ah! it was not &s;o in <HI>Flanders,</HI> when the <HI>French</HI> Wine and <HI>French</HI> Mony tumbled a|bout as if it wou'd never be Night&mdash;But Ba&s;ta! here comes my Ma&s;ter and his Friend Mr. <HI>Hearty&mdash;</HI>I mu&s;t ha&s;te and get our Di&s;gui&s;es&mdash;</P>
<L>And if Dame Fortune fails us now (to win her)</L>
<L>I'll &s;ay no more, but think the Devil's in her.</L>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Rovewell</HI> and <HI>Hearty.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o melancholly, Captain? Come, come, a Man of your Gaiety and Courage &s;hou'd never take a Di&s;appointment &s;o to Heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath, to be prevented when I had brought my De&s;ign &s;o near Perfection! an old &s;ubtle cro&s;s-grain'd Hunks&mdash;But have her I mu&s;t and will, or I am re&s;olv'd
<PB N="5" REF="5">
to burn the old Drone out of his Hive, and carry the Hony-comb away in Triumph.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very con&s;ciencious Re&s;olution truly&mdash;But, Captain, wou'd you be le&s;s open and daring in your Attempts, you might hope to &s;ucceed&mdash;The old Gentleman, you know, is cautious to a Degree; his Daughter is under a &s;trict Confinement; and wou'd you u&s;e more of the Fox than the Lion, Fortune may perhaps throw an Op|portunity in your Way&mdash;But you mu&s;t have Patience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who can have Patience when Dan|ger's &s;o near? Read this Letter, and tell me then what Room there is for Patience.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Hearty</HI> reads.</STAGE>
<LETTER>
<P>To Morrow will prevent all our vain Strug|gles to get to each other&mdash;I am then to be marry'd to my eternal Aver&s;ion&mdash;You know the Fop, it is <HI>Cuckoo,</HI> who having a large E&s;tate, is forc'd upon me; but my Heart can be none but <HI>Rovewell</HI>'s&mdash;Immediately after the Receipt of this, meet Betty <HI>at the old Place: There is yet one In|vention left; if you pur&s;ue it clo&s;ely, you may perhaps relea&s;e me, who wou'd be your Arethu&s;a.</HI></P>
</LETTER>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="6">
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, <HI>Arethu&s;a,</HI> I will relea&s;e thee or dye in the Attempt. Dear Friend, ex|cu&s;e my Rudene&s;s, you know the Rea&s;on.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, go thy Ways and get her, for thou de&s;erv'&s;t her&mdash;I find a Soldier's never idle&mdash;as &s;oon as he has done with his Enemy he attacks his Mi&s;tre&s;s, and &s;el|dom fails to conquer.</P>
<L>When true-bred <HI>Engli&s;h</HI> Courage takes the Field,</L>
<L>The <HI>Frenchmen</HI> and the Ladies quickly yield.</L>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="scene">
<STAGE>SCENE a Chamber.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Argus</HI> and <HI>Arethu&s;a.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<STAGE><HI>Arethu&s;a</HI> reads.</STAGE>
<L>See! &s;miling <HI>Cynthia,</HI> now begins to ri&s;e,</L>
<L>And add tran&s;parent Glories to the Skies.</L>
<L>Hail beauteous Rival of the dark &s;ome Night,</L>
<L>Who&s;e Glooms give way to thy &s;uperior Light!</L>
<L>Thy lucid Charms afford a &s;econd Day,</L>
<L>And guide the weary Pilgrim in his Way.</L>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Daughter, what Linguo is that &s;ame that you &s;putter out at this Rate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Engli&s;h,</HI> Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="7">
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Engli&s;h,</HI> quotha'! adad, I took it for Non&s;ence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis an Hymn to the Moon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Hymn to the Moon! a Hymn to the Devil, you Jade you&mdash;I'll have none of your Hymns in my Hou&s;e&mdash;Give me the Book, Mi&s;tre&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, Sir, there's no harm in reading a harmle&s;s Poem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me the Book, I &s;ay, Hu&s;wife&mdash;Poems with a Pox, what are they good for? But to blow up the fire of Love, and make young Wenches as hot as the De|vil&mdash;but I have taken care of you, Mi&s;tre&s;s, for to Morrow you &s;hall have a Husband to &s;tay your Stomach, and no le&s;s a Per&s;on than Squire <HI>Cuckoo.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will not be &s;o cruel to marry me to a Man I cannot love?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>But you mu&s;t and &s;hall love him, Hu&s;wife: What! you hone after a red Rag, I warrant you: Nothing le&s;s than a Captain will go down with you, for&s;ooth; a di&s;|banded Captain&mdash;Such a Fellow de&s;erves Twelve Thou&s;and Pounds to &s;quander away, does he? But I have put a Spoke in his Wheel&mdash;for to Morrow you &s;hall be bound Apprentice for Life, and then your disbanded Lover may e'en hang him&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="8">
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heav'n's &s;ake, dear Sir, give me a little time to con&s;ider: Marriage is a Con|cern of the utmo&s;t Con&s;equence&mdash;put it off for one Month, that I may endea|vour to make my Duty and De&s;ires go to|gether.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you your Duty, and a Fig for De&s;ires&mdash;No, no, Mi&s;tre&s;s; Delays are dangerous in the&s;e Ca&s;es&mdash;Mr. <HI>Cuckoo</HI> is a brisk young Fellow, and a little Fea|ther-bed Doctrine will &s;oon put the Cap|tain out of your Head&mdash;and to put you out of his Power, you &s;hall be given over to the Squire to Morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Sir, con&s;ider&mdash;put it off for a Week, let me have time to make the ne|ce&s;&s;ary Preparations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, to run away with the Cap|tain, Mi&s;tre&s;s?&mdash;no, no, to Morrow is the Day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely you will at lea&s;t defer it one Day?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, nor one Hour&mdash;to Mor|row Morning at eight of the Clock preci&s;e|ly&mdash;In the mean time, take Notice that the Squire's Si&s;ter is hourly expected, a good plain Country Girl, but a great For|tune&mdash;I believe it will be a Match between her and your Cou&s;in <HI>Frank&mdash;</HI>the old Folks have almo&s;t agreed about the
<PB N="9" REF="9">
Matter&mdash;&s;o pray do you be civil and &s;ociable with her, and let me have none of your Pouts and Louts, as you tender my Di&s;plea&s;ure.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>To Morrow is but &s;hort Warning&mdash;but we may be too cunning for you yet, old Gentleman.</P>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Betty.</HI></STAGE>
<P>O <HI>Betty!</HI> welcome a thou&s;and times over, What News&mdash;have you &s;een the Captain, <HI>Betty?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, and if you were to &s;ee him in his new Rigging, you'd &s;plit your Sides with laughing&mdash;&s;uch a Hoyden, &s;uch a piece of Country Stuff, you never &s;et your Eyes on&mdash;but the Petticoats are &s;oon thrown off, and if good Luck at|tends us, you may &s;oon conjure Mi&s;s <HI>Mal|kin,</HI> the Squire's Si&s;ter, into your own dear Captain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>But when will he come?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;tantly, Madam, he only &s;tays to &s;ettle Matters for our E&s;cape, he's in deep Con&s;ultation with his privy Coun&s;ellor <HI>Ro|bin,</HI> who is to attend him in the Quality of a Country Putt&mdash;They'll both be here in a Moment, &s;o let's in and pack up the Jew|els, that we may be ready at once to leap
<PB N="10" REF="10">
into the Saddle of Liberty, and ride full &s;peed to your De&s;ires.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear <HI>Betty,</HI> let's make ha&s;te, I think every Moment an Age 'till I'm free from this Bondage.</P>
<L>When Parents ob&s;tinate and cruel prove,</L>
<L>And force us to a Man we cannot Love,</L>
<L>'Tis fit we di&s;appoint the &s;ordid Elves,</L>
<L>And wi&s;ely get us Husbands for our &s;elves.</L>
<STAGE>[Knock here.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>There they are&mdash;in, in.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE>
<STAGE>[Knock again.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Argus.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're woundy ha&s;ty methinks, to knock at that rate&mdash;this is certainly &s;ome Courtier come to borrow Mony, I know it by the &s;awcy rapping of the Foot|man&mdash;Who's at the Door?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob. without.]</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Tummos.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Tummos!</HI> who's <HI>Tummos?</HI> Who wou'd you &s;peak with, Friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>With young Ma&s;ter's Vaather-in-Law that mun be, Mr. <HI>Hardguts.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what's your Bu&s;ine&s;s with Mr. <HI>Hardguts?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why young Mi&s;tre&s;s is come out o'
<PB N="11" REF="11">
the Country, to &s;ee Brother's Wife that mun be, that's all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Od&s;o; the Squire's Si&s;ter&mdash;I'm &s;orry I made 'em wait &s;o &s;ong.</P>
<STAGE>[Opens the Door.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Rovewell</HI> dre&s;t like a Country Gentle|woman, and <HI>Robin</HI> like a Country Clown.</STAGE>
<P>Save you fair Lady, you're welcome to Town: <STAGE>[Salutes him.]</STAGE> A very mode&s;t come|ly Maiden truly. How long have you been in Town, Lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why an Hour and a bit, or &s;o&mdash;we ju&s;t put up our Hor&s;es at <HI>King's-Arms</HI> yonder, and &s;taid a crum to zee poor things feed or &s;o, for your <HI>London</HI> O&s;tlers give lit|tle enough to poor Bea&s;ts, and you &s;tond not by 'em your zel, and zee 'em fed, they'll cheat you to your Face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg</SPEAKER>
<P>Why how now Clodpate? Are you to &s;peak before your Mi&s;tre&s;s? With your Hat on too? Is that your Country breed|ing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why an it's on, it's on, an it's off, it's off&mdash;what cares <HI>Tummos?</HI> for your fal&s;e-hearted <HI>London</HI> Compliments&mdash;an you'd have an an&s;wer from young Mi|&s;tre&s;s, you mun look to <HI>Tummos&mdash;</HI>for &s;he's &s;o main ba&s;hful, &s;he never &s;peaks one
<PB N="12" REF="12">
Word but her Prayers, and tho&s;en &s;o &s;oftly that no Body can hear her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>I like her the better&mdash;for Si|lence is a heav'nly Virtue in a Woman&mdash;but very rare to be found in this wicked Place&mdash;Have you &s;een your Brother, pretty Lady, &s;ince you came to Town? <STAGE>[<HI>Rovewell</HI> Curt&s;ies.]</STAGE> O miraculous Mode|&s;ty! wou'd all Women were thus? Can't you &s;peak, Madam?</P>
<STAGE>[Curt&s;ies again.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>An you get a Word from her, 'tis more than &s;he has &s;poken to us the&s;e four|&s;core and &s;even long Miles&mdash;but young Mi&s;tre&s;s will prate fa&s;t enough an you &s;et her among&s;t your Women Volk, or &s;o, when &s;he's once acquainted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg</SPEAKER>
<P>Say'&s;t thou &s;o, hone&s;t Fellow, then I'll &s;end her to tho&s;e that have Tongue e|nough I'll warrant you&mdash;Here <HI>Betty.</HI></P>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Betty.</HI></STAGE>
<P>Take this young Lady to my Daughter, 'tis Squire <HI>Cuckoo</HI>'s Si&s;ter; and d'ye hear? make much of her, I charge you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir&mdash;plea&s;e to follow me, Madam.</P>
<STAGE>[Ex. <HI>Betty</HI> and <HI>Rovewell.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well hone&s;t Friend, and where's the Squire?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why one cannot find a Mon out in this &s;ame <HI>London,</HI> there are &s;o many Ta|veruns and Chockling-Hou&s;en, you may as well &s;eek a Needle in a Hay Fardel, as they &s;ayn in the Country&mdash;I was at Squire's Lodging yonder, and there was no body, but a prate a pace whor&s;on of a Footboy, and he told me Mai&s;ter was at Chockling-Hou&s;e, and the while the Vixen did nothing but taunt and laugh at me, or &s;o&mdash;I Cod I cou'd have found in my Heart to have given a good wherrit i'th' Chops, &s;o I cou'd&mdash;&s;o I went to one Chockling-Hou&s;e, and Squire was not there, and &s;o I went to t'other Chockling-Hou&s;e, and t'other, 'till I was a weary, and I cou'd &s;ee nothing but a many People &s;upping hot Suppings, and reading your Gazate Papers &s;o we came away here and plea&s;e you, but we had much ado to find out your Wor&s;hip's Hou&s;e, the vixen Boys &s;et us a thick a &s;ide, and a thack a &s;ide, that we were almo&s;t lo&s;t&mdash;an it were not for an hone&s;t Fellow that came and &s;how|ed us the right way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's a pity they &s;hou'd u&s;e Strangers &s;o&mdash;but as to your young Mi&s;tre&s;s, does &s;he never &s;peak?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Adod, Sir, never to a Mon, why &s;he wo'not &s;peak to her own Father, &s;he's &s;o main ba&s;hful or &s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's &s;trange indeed&mdash;but how does my Friend Sir <HI>Roger?&mdash;</HI>he's well, I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hearty &s;till, Sir&mdash;he has drunk down &s;ix Fox-hunters &s;in la&s;t <HI>Lammas&mdash;</HI>he holds old cour&s;e &s;till; twenty Pipes a Day, a Cup of Mum in the Morning, a Tankard of Ale at Noon, and three Bot|tles of Stingo at Night&mdash;the &s;ame Mon now he was thirty Years ago, or &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good now, good now! but wou'd&s;t drink, hone&s;t Friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't care an I do a bit or &s;o, for to tell you the truth, I'm main dry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, <HI>John.</HI></P>
<STAGE>Enter Servant.</STAGE>
<P>Take this hone&s;t Fellow down, and make him welcome&mdash;when your Mi&s;tre&s;s is ready to go, we'll call you.</P>
<STAGE>[Exeunt <HI>Robin</HI> and Servant.</STAGE>
<P>The&s;e Country Fellows are very blunt, but very hone&s;t&mdash;I wou'd fain hear his Mi|&s;tre&s;s talk&mdash;he &s;aid &s;he'd find her Tongue when &s;he was among&s;t tho&s;e of her own Sex&mdash;I'll go li&s;ten for once, and hear what the young Tits have to &s;ay to one another.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="scene">
<PB N="15" REF="15">
<STAGE>SCENE a Chamber.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Rovewell, Arethu&s;a,</HI> and <HI>Betty.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear <HI>Arethu&s;a!</HI> delay not the time thus&mdash;your Father will certainly come in, and &s;urprize us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's make Hay while the Sun &s;hines, Madam, I long to be out of this Pri&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>So do I, but not on the Captain's Conditions, to be his Pri&s;oner for Life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall run mad if you trifle thus&mdash;name your Conditions&mdash;I &s;ign my con&s;ent before-hand</P>
<STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;es her.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg. li&s;tning.]</SPEAKER>
<P>So, &s;o, this is as it &s;hou'd be&mdash;they are as gracious as can be already&mdash;how the young Tit &s;muggles her&mdash;adod, &s;he ki&s;&s;es with a hearty good Will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>O the great Romp, he takes one's Breath away&mdash;how cou'd you pa&s;s upon my Father? I never &s;aw &s;uch a hoyden ma&s;|culine Mon&s;ter in my Life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let's once get out I'll tell you the whole Story&mdash;this is no Time or Place for Particulars&mdash;if you lov'd me, or valu'd your own Happine&s;s, you wou'd not trifle away this Opportunity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="16" REF="16">
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed Captain, I'm afraid to tru&s;t you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Captain! how's this&mdash;ble&s;s my Eye-&s;ight&mdash;I know the Villain now, but I'll be even with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, dear Madam, don't trifle &s;o, I long to &s;ee you both between a pair of Sheets&mdash;the Par&s;on's at the very next Door, you'll be tackt together in the twinkling of a Bed&s;taff, and then I'll tru&s;t you to come back to your Cage again, if you can do it with a &s;afe Con&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a treacherous Jade! I'll do your Bu&s;ine&s;s for you, Mrs. <HI>Jezabel.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, Madam, what a Life you lead here, what a jealous, ill-natur'd, watch|ful, covetous, barbarous, ob&s;tinate old Cuff of a Father you have to deal with&mdash;what a glorious Opportunity this is? And what a &s;ad, &s;ad, very &s;ad thing it is, to die a Maid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Whore, I cou'd &s;lit her No&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>In &s;hort, Madam, if you &s;tay much longer, you may repent it every Vein in your Heart&mdash;the old Hunks will undoubt|edly pop in upon us, and di&s;cover all, and then we're undone for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>You may be damn'd for ever, Mrs. Impudence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="17" REF="17">
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Captain, if you &s;hou'd de|ceive me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I do, may Heav'n&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, no &s;wearing Captain, for fear you &s;hou'd break your Oath.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>How can you doubt me, <HI>Arethu&s;a,</HI> when you know how much I love&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah wheedling Dog! but I'll &s;poil his Sport anon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come away, dear Madam&mdash;I have the Jewels&mdash;but &s;tay, I'll go fir&s;t to &s;ee if the Coa&s;t be clear.</P>
<STAGE>[Going out, <HI>Argus</HI> &s;tops her.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where are you going, pretty Maiden?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only do&mdash;do&mdash;down Stairs, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what ha&s;t thou got there, Child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Bet.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing but Pi&mdash;Pi&mdash;Pins, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, give me the Pins&mdash;and do you go to Hell, Mrs. <HI>Minx,</HI> d'ye hear? Out of my Hou&s;e this Minute, or expect the dreadful I&s;&s;ue of my righteous Indigna|tion.
<STAGE>[Thru&s;ts her out.]</STAGE>
<HI>O Tempora! O Mo|res!</HI> what an Age is this? Get you in for|&s;ooth, I'll talk with you anon&mdash;So, Captain, are tho&s;e your Regimental Cloaths? I'll a&s;|&s;ure you they become you mightily, if you did but &s;ee your &s;elf now, how much like a Hero you look. <STAGE>[Laughs.]</STAGE> But, Cap|tain, an't you an impudent Dog now, an't
<PB N="18" REF="18">
you?&mdash;mu&s;t no Body &s;erve your Turn but my Daughter? nothing le&s;s than twelve thou&s;and Pounds? Well, I find you Soldiers rate your &s;elves high&mdash;but you de&s;erve it in Truth: you work your Brains, you try Stratagems, you transform into a thou&s;and Shapes to catch a Fortune<HI>&mdash;Ecce Signum,</HI> ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sblood and Fury, &s;top your Grin|ning, or I'll &s;tretch your Mouth with a Vengeance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, Captain <HI>Bell&s;wagger,</HI> if you're &s;o pa&s;&s;ionate it's high time to call Aid and A&s;&s;i&s;tance: Here <HI>Richard, Thomas, John,</HI> help me to lay hold on this Fellow; you have no Sword now, Captain, no Sword, d'ye mark me, ha, ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Servants and <HI>Robin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I have a Pi&s;tol, Sir, at your Ser|vice.</P>
<STAGE>[Claps a Pi&s;tol to his Brea&s;t.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Lord! O Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll unload it in your Brea&s;t, if you &s;tir one Step after me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A bloody-minded Dog.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;ee here, Gentlemen, here are two little Bull-dogs of the &s;ame Breed, they are wonderful Scowrers of the Brain&mdash;So that if you offer to mole&s;t or follow us&mdash;
<PB N="19" REF="19">
you under&s;tand me, Gentlemen, you under|&s;tand me.</P>
<STAGE>[Ex. <HI>Rovewell</HI> and <HI>Robin.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, we under&s;tand you with a Pox.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Devil go with 'em, I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter <HI>Rovewell</HI> and <HI>Robin.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>All.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Lord! O Lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, we did not fol|low you, we didn't indeed, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>D'ye hear, old Gentleman, I'll have your Daughter, if I wade to her thro' the Blood of you and your whole Generati|on; and &s;o good-bye t'ye, old Goo&s;e-Cap.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, good-bye t'ye in the Devil's Name&mdash;a terrible Dog! What a Fright he has put me in! I &s;han't be my &s;elf this Month&mdash;And you, ye cowardly Ra|&s;cals, to &s;tand by and &s;ee my Life in Dan|ger&mdash;Get out, ye Slaves, out of my Hou&s;e I &s;ay.</P>
<STAGE>[Drives them out.</STAGE>
<P>What a murthering Son of a Whore is this? but I'll prevent him&mdash;he &s;hall eat Brick, and Stone, and Iron to get at her again, I'll warrant him&mdash;But to Morrow &s;he &s;hall be marry'd certainly, and then my furious Gentleman can have no Hopes left&mdash;A <HI>Jezabel,</HI> to love a
<PB N="20" REF="20">
Red-Coat without any Money&mdash;Had he but Money, if he wanted Sen&s;e, Man|ners, or even Manhood it&s;elf, it matter'd not a Pin&mdash;but to want Mony is the Devil&mdash;Well, I'll &s;ecure her under Lock and Key 'till to Morrow; and if her Husband can't keep her from Captain|hunting, e'en let her bring him home a fre&s;h Pair of Horns every time &s;he goes out up|on the Cha&s;e.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="scene">
<STAGE>SCENE a Chamber.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Arethu&s;a</HI> &s;itting melancholly on a Couch, enter to her <HI>Argus.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Lady, you're welcome home&mdash;See how the pretty Turtle &s;its moaning the Lo&s;s of her Mate&mdash;What, not a Word, <HI>Thu&s;y!</HI> not a Word, Child! Come, come, don't be in the Dumps &s;o, and I'll fetch the Captain, or the Squire's Si&s;ter, perhaps they may make it prattle a bit. Ah, ungracious Hu&s;wife! is all my Care come to this? Is this the Gratitude you &s;hew to your Uncle's Memory! to throw away (what he bu&s;tled &s;o hardly for) at &s;o mad a Rate! Did he leave you twelve thou&s;and Pounds, think you, to make you no better
<PB N="21" REF="21">
than a Soldier's Trull, to follow a Camp, to carry a Knap&s;ack? This is what you'd have, Mi&s;tre&s;s, is it not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>This, or ten thou&s;and times wor&s;e, were better with the Man I love, than to be chain'd to the nau&s;eous Embraces of one I hate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well, Mrs. <HI>Termagant,</HI> very well! this is the way you an&s;wer your Fa|ther, is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>You never found me guilty of this Language, Sir, 'till now your U&s;age forc'd me to it&mdash;My Uncle left my Porti|on entirely at my own Di&s;po&s;al, knowing your Covetou&s;ne&s;s wou'd prompt you to force me again&s;t my Inclinations&mdash;Mr. <HI>Cuckoo</HI> is a Fop, who&s;e Affectation and Ignorance I abhor&mdash;Captain <HI>Rovewell</HI> has Merit, Sen&s;e, and Courage&mdash;I love him, and can be happy in no other, and no other will I have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>So! &s;o! very pretty! very pretty indeed! I tell you, Mrs. <HI>Snapdragon,</HI> you &s;hall have Squire <HI>Cuckoo,</HI> and no other, or the Devil a Penny &s;hall you have of mine; mark that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Uncle, Sir, has left me enough to make my &s;elf happy; and you are free to di&s;po&s;e of your own as you plea&s;e&mdash;
<PB N="22" REF="22">
but me you never &s;hall again&s;t my Inclina|tions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very dutiful Lady indeed! I'll make you &s;ing another Song to Morrow, Mi&s;tre&s;s; and 'till then I'll leave you in <HI>Salv&acirc; Cu&s;todi&acirc;</HI> to con&s;ider&mdash;bye <HI>Thu|&s;y.</HI></P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>How barbarous is the Covetou&s;ne&s;s and Caution of ill-natur'd Parents; they toil for E&s;tates to make Po&s;terity happy, and then by mi&s;taken Prudence they match us to our Aver&s;ion&mdash;Thus while they mea&s;ure Happine&s;s by Riches, they only &s;eek to make their Children mi&s;era|rable&mdash;But I am re&s;olv'd not to &s;uf|fer tamely however&mdash;They &s;hall find, tho' my Body's weak, my Re&s;olution's &s;trong; and I may yet find Spirit enough to plague 'em.</P>
<L>Sooner than I'll forego the Man I prize,</L>
<L>I'll brave 'em, tho' I fall a Sacrifice.</L>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="scene">
<PB N="23" REF="23">
<STAGE>SCENE the Street.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Hearty.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>O' my Con&s;cience I think this young Fellow will run mad&mdash;So many Enterprizes and Di&s;appointments upon the Back of each other &s;hou'd pall him me|thinks&mdash;but yet he holds out couragiou&s;ly, and is &s;till as vigorous as ever&mdash;What he is upon now I know not, but he &s;wears he'll carry her&mdash;I wi&s;h he is not balk'd, for the old Fellow is more upon his Guard now than ever.</P>
<P>How have I been deceiv'd in this Boy! I find him the very Rever&s;e of what his Step|mother repre&s;ented him&mdash;and am now &s;en|&s;ible it was only her ill U&s;age that forc'd my Child away&mdash;His not having &s;een me &s;ince he was five Years old renders me a perfect Stranger to him&mdash;under that Pre|tence I have got into his Acquaintance, and find him all I cou'd wi&s;h&mdash;Here he comes, big with another Plot&mdash;but if it fails, I believe my Mony mu&s;t buy him the Girl at la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="24" REF="24">Enter <HI>Rovewell.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, my dear Friend here already; this is kind.</P>
<STAGE>[Draws his Sword, and makes a Signal.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter Boy.</STAGE>
<P>Is your Mi&s;tre&s;s lock'd up, &s;ay you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, and <HI>Betty</HI>'s turn'd away, and all the Men Servants; and there's no living Soul in the Hou&s;e but our old Cookmaid, and I, and my Ma&s;ter, and Mrs. <HI>Thu&s;y,</HI> and &s;he cries, and cries, and cries her Eyes out almo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>O the tormenting News! If the Garri&s;on is &s;o weak, the Ca&s;tle may be the &s;ooner &s;torm'd&mdash;But how did you get out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thro' the Kitchin-Window, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew me the Window pre&s;ently.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alack-a-day, it won't do indeed, Sir, that Plot won't take.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Sirrah?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are &s;omething too big, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll try that however.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, Sir, you can't get your Leg in, but I cou'd put you in the Way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, dear Boy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="25" REF="25">
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can lend you the Key of Mrs. <HI>Thu&s;y</HI>'s Chamber&mdash;if you can contrive to get in|to the Hou&s;e&mdash;but you mu&s;t be &s;ure to let my Mi&s;tre&s;s out.</P>
<STAGE>[Gives a Key.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>How coud'&s;t thou get it? This is almo&s;t a Miracle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>I pick'd it out of my Ma&s;ter's Coat-Pocket, Sir, this Morning, when I was a bru&s;hing him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's my Boy&mdash;there, there's Mony for you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Boy.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Ma&s;ter will mi&s;s me, Sir, I mu&s;t go, but I wi&s;h you good Luck.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Robin,</HI> and four Soldiers.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>So my Hearts of Oak, are you all ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>All.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir, yes, and it plea&s;e your no|ble Honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rove.</SPEAKER>
<P>You know your Cue then&mdash;Serjeant to your Po&s;t.</P>
<STAGE>[Places the Soldiers out of &s;ight, then knocks loud.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, are you all a&s;leep, and dead, in this Hou&s;e, that they can't hear one knock?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="26" REF="26">Enter <HI>Argus.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are very ha&s;ty, Sir, methinks.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Bu&s;ine&s;s, Sir, requires ha&s;te!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Bu&s;ine&s;s! pray what is your Bu&s;ine&s;s, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Bu&s;ine&s;s, Sir, is to borrow a thou&s;and Pound of you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very conci&s;e indeed! but upon what Security, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon what Security! upon my own, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your mo&s;t humble Servant, you mu&s;t excu&s;e me, I don't lend Mony at that rate&mdash;a thou&s;and Pound upon thy Security, ha, ha, ha, did&s;t ever &s;ee a thou&s;and Pence of thy own&mdash;pray, Sir, what Countryman are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath, Sir, do you mean to affront me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>O by no means, Sir; only to &s;hut the Door, and keep the thou&s;and Pound to my &s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I mu&s;t have Satisfaction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get you gone Fellow, you want to rob me, do you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sblood, and Fire, and Fury!</P>
<STAGE>[Lays hold of him, and pulls him out of the Hou&s;e, the Soldiers &s;eize him, blind|fold
<PB N="27" REF="27">
him, and gag him, and &s;tand o|ver him with drawn Swords: <HI>Robin</HI> and Captain go in and bring out <HI>Are|thu&s;a,</HI> and carry her off&mdash;then the Soldiers ungag <HI>Argus,</HI> and run off.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thieves, Thieves.</P>
<STAGE>[Pulls off the blindfold.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Mob.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the matter, what's the mat|ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Neighbours I'm robb'd, and mur|ther'd, ruin'd and undone for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what's the matter, Ma&s;ter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's a whole Legion of Thieves in my Hou&s;e, they gagg'd me, and blind|folded me, and offer'd forty naked Swords at my Brea&s;t&mdash;I beg of you to a&s;&s;i&s;t me, or they'll &s;trip the Hou&s;e in a Minute.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forty drawn Swords, &s;ay you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and more I think on my Con|&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then look ye, Sir, I am a mar|ry'd Man, and have a Family, and I wou'd not venture among&s;t &s;uch a parcel of Blood|thir&s;ty Rogues for the World; but if you plea&s;e, I'll run and call a Con&s;table.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="28" REF="28">
<SPEAKER>Omnes.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, call a Con&s;table, call a Con&s;table.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg,</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;han't have a Penny left, if we &s;tay for a Con&s;table&mdash;I am but one Man, and as old as I am, I'll lead the way if you'll follow me.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Omnes.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, in, in, follow, follow, Huzzi!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prithee <HI>Jack</HI> do you go in, and &s;ee what's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, do you go in, and you come to that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>I go in, what &s;hou'd I go in for? I have lo&s;t nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wom.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, no body to help the poor old Gentleman? If I was a Man l'd follow him my &s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you then? What oc|ca&s;ion have I to be kill'd for him, or you either, ha!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter &s;econd Mob and Con&s;table.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Omnes.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's Mr. Con&s;table, here's Mr. Con&s;table.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence, in the King's Name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Omnes.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Silence, Silence!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's the meaning of this Riot, who makes all this Di&s;turbance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you, Mr. Con&s;table.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="29" REF="29">
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>And plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip, let me &s;peak.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, this Man talks like a Man of Parts&mdash;What's the matter, Friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>And plea&s;e your noble Wor&s;hip's Honour, we are his Maje&s;ty's Liege Sub|jects, and were terrified out of our Habita|tions and dwelling Places by a Cry from a|broad; which your noble Wor&s;hip mu&s;t under&s;tand was occa&s;ionable by the Gentle|man of this Houfe, who was &s;o unfortuna|ble as to be kill'd by Thieves, who are now in his Hou&s;e to the Numbration of above &s;orty, and plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip, all com|pleatly arm'd with Powder and Ball&mdash;Back&s;words, Pi&s;tols, Bayonets, and Blunder|bu&s;&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what is to be done in this Ca&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why and plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip, knowing your noble Honour to be the King's Maje&s;ty's noble Officer of the Peace&mdash;we thought 'twas be&s;t your Honour &s;hou'd come and terrifie the&s;e Rogues a|way with your noble Authority.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;aid, very well &s;aid indeed&mdash;Gentlemen, I am the King's Officer, and I command you in the King's Name to aid and a&s;&s;i&s;t me to call them Rogues out of the Hou&s;e&mdash;Who's within there? I Charge you come out in the King's Name,
<PB N="30" REF="30">
and &s;ubmit your &s;elves to my Royal Au|thority.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Argus.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the Gentleman that was kill'd, and plea&s;e your Wor&s;hip.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Neighbours! I am ruin'd and un|done for ever&mdash;they have taken away all that's dear to me in the World.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's his Mony&mdash;'tis a &s;ad covetous Dog.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what's the matter? What have they done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>O they have taken my Child from me, my <HI>Thu&s;a.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good lack!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry come up&mdash;what Valua|tion can &s;he be&mdash;but have they taken no|thing el&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would they had &s;tript my Hou&s;e of every Pennyworth, &s;o they had left my Child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a Lie, I believe&mdash;for he loves his Mony beyond his Soul, and wou'd &s;ooner part with that, than a Groat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the Captain's doings&mdash;but I'll have him hang'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>But where are the Thieves?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gone, gone, beyond all hopes of pur&s;uit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>3 Mob.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, are they gone then&mdash;come, Neighbours, let's go in, and kill eve|ry Mother's Child of 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Con.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, I charge you to commit no Murderation&mdash;follow me, and we'll ap|prehend 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go Villains, Cowards, Cuckolds, Scoundrels, or I &s;hall &s;u&s;pect you are the Thieves that mean to rob me of what is yet left&mdash;how brave you are now the Danger's over&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>[Drives 'em off.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Rovewell, Hearty,</HI> and <HI>Arethu&s;a.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me! who have we got here? O <HI>Thu&s;y! Thu&s;y!</HI> I had rather never have &s;een thee again, than to have found thee in &s;uch Company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I hope my Husband's Company is not criminal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Husband! who's your Hus|band? Hu&s;wife? That Scoundrel, that No-Captain&mdash;out of my &s;ight thou ungracious Wretch&mdash;I'll go make my Will this Mi|nute&mdash;and you you Villain, how dare you look me in the Face after this? I'll have you hang'd; I will, Sirrah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>O fie, Brother <HI>Argus,</HI> moderate your Pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;you don't do well to abu&s;e your Son-in-Law at this rate&mdash;It ill be|comes the Friend&s;hip you owe <HI>Ned Worthy,</HI> to villifie and affront his only Child, and for no other Crime than improving that Friend&s;hip which has ever been between us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! my dear Friend alive! I heard thou wer't dead in the <HI>Indies:</HI> And is that thy Son! and my God&s;on if I am not mi|&s;taken!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>The very &s;ame&mdash;the la&s;t and be&s;t Remains of our Family&mdash;forc'd by my Wife's Cruelty and my Ab&s;ence to the Army&mdash;my Wife is &s;ince dead, and the Son &s;he had by her fir&s;t Husband, whom &s;he intended to Heir my E&s;tate&mdash;but Fortune guided me by Chance to my dear Boy, who after twenty Years ab&s;ence, and changing my Name, knew me not&mdash;'till I ju&s;t now di&s;cover'd my &s;elf to him, and your fair Daughter, whom I will make him de&s;erve by thirty thou&s;and Pound, which I brought from <HI>India&mdash;</HI>be&s;ide what E&s;tate I may leave him at my Death.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And to match that, old Boy&mdash;my Daughter &s;hall have every Penny of mine, be&s;ides her Uncle's Legacy. Ah you young Rogue! had I known you before, I wou'd
<PB N="33" REF="33">
not have us'd you &s;o roughly&mdash;but now you have won my Girl &s;o bravely, take her and welcome&mdash;but you mu&s;t excu&s;e all Faults&mdash;the old Man meant all for the be&s;t&mdash;you mu&s;t not be angry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Capt.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, on the contrary, we ought to beg your Pardon for the many Di&s;quiets we have given you&mdash;and with your Pardon, we hope for your Ble&s;&s;ing.</P>
<STAGE>[Kneels.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Rob.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I hope you'll forgive me too, for truly, Sir, if my Ma&s;ter's Nece&s;&s;ity had not oblig'd me to it, I had never troubled your Wor&s;hip for a thou&s;and Pound at once, but the next time I do (being you doubted my Word) I'll give you my Bond for the Payment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll give you my Bond that you &s;hall be hang'd if you do. But I'll forgive you, you Rogue, tho' you don't de&s;erve it, Sir|rah&mdash;Well, ble&s;s you both my dear Chil|dren&mdash;ah the little Rogues, how pretty they look&mdash;come, bu&s;s and Friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavn's ble&s;s you together&mdash;now old School-fellow, what &s;ay'&s;t to a Grand|&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, that wou'd be &s;omewhat indeed&mdash;but who doubts it&mdash;the young Rogue looks vigorous, he has it in him, I'll war|rant him: But, Brother <HI>Worthy,</HI> how cam'&s;t alive again?&mdash;I heard for a Certainty you were dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="34" REF="34">
<SPEAKER>Hear.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was very near Death, 'tis true&mdash;but Fortune protected me&mdash;every Ship in the Fleet was lo&s;t but mine&mdash;which tho' it was deeply laden, e&s;caped, and brought me Home &s;afe with a Cargo, worth thirty thou&s;and Pounds, which &s;hall be &s;ettled on my Boy to Morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>My <HI>Thu&s;y,</HI> Sir, &s;han't be behind hand&mdash;But Hu&s;&s;y, what makes you in &s;uch a brown Study? Why don't you ki&s;s your old Father&mdash;adod, I am &s;o tran&s;ported, I can't tell whether I'm alive or dead.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Are.</SPEAKER>
<P>May your Joy be everla&s;ting.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Arg.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will, you Jade,&mdash;Come Son, you mu&s;t make my Hou&s;e your own&mdash;for the future: Brother <HI>Worthy,</HI> you &s;hall lodge here too: Come, let's in.</P>
</SP>
<L>In vain we &s;trive to force a Woman's Will:</L>
<L>Do what we can, they'll get the better &s;till.</L>
</DIV1>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
